⚙️ Role of the LaunchDarkly Kill‑Switch Library
The library (LDKillSwitch) provides a cached wrapper around the LaunchDarkly SDK. Its components:

Component	File	Responsibility
Cache	cache.go	In‑memory TTL cache (go-cache) storing boolean flag values. Cache key = flagKey:contextKey.
Service	service.go	Simple facade that calls the cache.
Config	config.go	Holds SDK key, offline mode, cache TTL, max size.
LD Client	ld_client.go	Initializes the official LaunchDarkly client. Supports offline mode (reads flags.json) and optional Redis persistence.
Flag Evaluation Logic (inside cache.GetBooleanFlagValue)
text
if cacheEnabled and key exists in cache → return cached value
else:
    fresh = ldClient.BoolVariation(flagKey, context, defaultValue)
    store in cache with TTL
    return fresh
Cache TTL = expireAfterWriteMinute minutes (from config, here 2 minutes).

MaximumSize is currently not used (go-cache does not support size limits out of the box; the code ignores it).

Offline Mode & flags.json
Because config.yaml sets offline: true, the LaunchDarkly client never contacts LaunchDarkly servers. Instead, ld_client.go configures a file data source pointing to flags.json. The SDK evaluates the flag rules locally using the JSON definition.

Current flags.json:

json
"location-feature-flag": {
  "on": true,
  "targets": [{ "values": ["LOC123"], "variation": 0 }],
  "fallthrough": { "variation": 1 },
  "variations": [false, true]
}
Variation 0 = false (kill‑switch ON)

Variation 1 = true (kill‑switch OFF)

Result: For context key "LOC123" → false; for any other key → true.

